  "prompt": "How do I know who is following me on Snapchat?",
  "response": "Snapchat primarily operates on a **friends-based system** rather than a traditional follower model like Instagram or Twitter. This means that interactions are typically between mutual friends rather than one-way followers. However, there are ways to see who has added you and who is interacting with your content. Here's how you can manage and view your connections on Snapchat:\n\n### 1. Viewing Your Friends List\n\nYour **Friends List** contains all the Snapchat users you've added or who have added you back.\n\n- **On Mobile:**\n  1. Open the Snapchat app.\n  2. Tap on your profile icon (Bitmoji or initials) in the top-left corner.\n  3. Scroll down to the \"Friends\" section to see your list of friends.\n\n### 2. Seeing Who Added You\n\nWhile Snapchat doesn't provide a direct \"followers\" feature, you can identify new friends or those who have recently added you:\n\n- **Friend Suggestions:**\n  Snapchat may suggest friends in the \"Add Friends\" section based on mutual connections, location, or contacts.\n  \n- **Quick Add:**\n  This feature shows a list of people you might know and have the option to add them as friends.\n\n### 3. Viewing Story Viewers\n\nIf you've posted **Stories** on Snapchat, you can see who has viewed them:\n\n- **On Mobile:**\n  1. Go to your Story by tapping on your profile icon.\n  2. Swipe up on the screen while viewing your Story.\n  3. A list of usernames who have viewed each snap in your Story will appear.\n\n### 4. Checking Interactions\n\nYou can also see who is interacting with your snaps and stories:\n\n- **Chat and Snaps:**\n  Any direct interactions through chats or sent snaps indicate that the other person is interested in your content.\n\n### 5. Public Profiles (For Creators)\n\nIf you have a **public profile** (typically for influencers, celebrities, or publishers):\n\n- You can gain **Subscribers** who follow your public stories without requiring mutual friendship.\n- To check your subscribers:\n  1. Go to your profile.\n  2. Look for the \"Subscribers\" section to see who is following your public content.\n\n### 6. Privacy Settings\n\nTo manage who can add you or view your content:\n\n1. **Open Snapchat** and go to your profile.\n2. Tap the **gear icon** (Settings) in the top-right corner.\n3. Review and adjust settings under sections like **\"Who Can\u2026\"**\n   - **Who Can Contact Me**\n   - **Who Can View My Story**\n   - **See My Location**\n\n### 7. Avoid Third-Party Apps\n\nBe cautious of third-party apps or services claiming to show your Snapchat followers or provide detailed analytics. These are often unreliable and can compromise your account's security.\n\n### Summary\n\n- **Snapchat uses a mutual friends system** rather than followers.\n- **View your friends** through your profile.\n- **Check Story viewers** to see who is engaging with your content.\n- **Public profiles** allow for subscribers if you qualify as a creator.\n- **Manage privacy settings** to control who can interact with you.\n\nIf Snapchat introduces new features related to followers in the future, it's a good idea to check the **official Snapchat support** pages or updates within the app for the latest information.",
